<collectingCountry id="F3679EAFFF94FFB1FB50F9FAFAD30841" box="[1210,1280,1606,1628]" name="Brazil" pageId="49" pageNumber="494">Brazil</collectingCountry>
and throughout the Gulf of Mexico, 
<quantity id="4C8873DAFF94FFB1FB71F9D9FACA0867" box="[1179,1305,1637,1658]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.4" metricValueMax="8.78" metricValueMin="4.02" pageId="49" pageNumber="494" unit="m" value="640.0" valueMax="878.0" valueMin="402.0">402–878 m</quantity>
(as 220– 480 fathoms) (
<bibRefCitation id="EFE1A3CEFF94FFB1FC35F93FFB580885" author="Rathbun MJ" box="[991,1163,1667,1689]" pageId="49" pageNumber="494" pagination="1 - 461" refId="ref75227" refString="Rathbun MJ. 1918. The grapsoid crabs of America. United States National Museum Bulletin 97: 1 - 461." type="journal article" year="1918">Rathbun, 1918</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE1A3CEFF94FFB1FB7DF938FA890884" author="Pequegnat LH &amp; Pequegnat WE" box="[1175,1370,1667,1689]" pageId="49" pageNumber="494" pagination="125 - 170" refId="ref74282" refString="Pequegnat LH, Pequegnat WE. 1970. Deep-sea anomurans of superfamily Galatheoidea with descriptions of three new species. In: Pequegnat WE, Chace FA Jr, eds. Contributions on the Biology of the Gulf of Mexico. Texas A &amp; M University Oceanographic Studies. Houston: Gulf Publishing Company, 125 - 170." type="book chapter" year="1970">Pequegnat, 1970</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BCFDE3FFF94FFB1FCD0F90EFC6008FB" blockId="49.[826,1442,1713,1766]" pageId="49" pageNumber="494">
<emphasis id="B904022DFF94FFB1FCD0F90EFBAF08DA" box="[826,1148,1714,1735]" italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="494">Occurrence at vents or seeps</emphasis>
: Bush Hill site, off 
<collectingRegion id="49B410DDFF94FFB1FCD0F96CFC7C08FB" box="[826,943,1744,1766]" country="United States of America" name="Louisiana" pageId="49" pageNumber="494">Louisiana</collectingRegion>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BCFDE3FFF94FFB2FCD0F942FD260EE5" blockId="49.[826,1442,1790,1904]" lastBlockId="50.[142,758,195,248]" lastPageId="50" lastPageNumber="495" pageId="49" pageNumber="494">
<emphasis id="B904022DFF94FFB1FCD0F942FC4E090E" box="[826,925,1790,1811]" italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="494">Material</emphasis>
: Abundant non-vent material was listed by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE1A3CEFF94FFB1FCD0F8A1FC21092E" author="Rathbun MJ" box="[826,1010,1821,1843]" pageId="49" pageNumber="494" pagination="1 - 461" refId="ref75227" refString="Rathbun MJ. 1918. The grapsoid crabs of America. United States National Museum Bulletin 97: 1 - 461." type="journal article" year="1918">Rathbun (1918)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE1A3CEFF94FFB1FBDEF8A1FAD1092E" author="Pequegnat LH &amp; Pequegnat WE" box="[1076,1282,1821,1843]" pageId="49" pageNumber="494" pagination="125 - 170" refId="ref74282" refString="Pequegnat LH, Pequegnat WE. 1970. Deep-sea anomurans of superfamily Galatheoidea with descriptions of three new species. In: Pequegnat WE, Chace FA Jr, eds. Contributions on the Biology of the Gulf of Mexico. Texas A &amp; M University Oceanographic Studies. Houston: Gulf Publishing Company, 125 - 170." type="book chapter" year="1970">Pequegnat (1970)</bibRefCitation>
. Although no specimens appear to have been collected from the Bush Hill site, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE1A3CEFF94FFB1FBE8F8E6FB00096D" author="Pequegnat LH &amp; Pequegnat WE" box="[1026,1235,1882,1904]" pageId="49" pageNumber="494" pagination="125 - 170" refId="ref74282" refString="Pequegnat LH, Pequegnat WE. 1970. Deep-sea anomurans of superfamily Galatheoidea with descriptions of three new species. In: Pequegnat WE, Chace FA Jr, eds. Contributions on the Biology of the Gulf of Mexico. Texas A &amp; M University Oceanographic Studies. Houston: Gulf Publishing Company, 125 - 170." type="book chapter" year="1970">Pequegnat (1970)</bibRefCitation>
listed abundant material from 
<emphasis id="B904022DFF97FFB2FED2FF7FFE770EC5" box="[312,420,195,216]" italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="495">Alaminos</emphasis>
deep-sea collections, some of which may have come from oil-seep areas (see below).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BCFDE3FFF97FFB2FF64FEACFE7A0D32" blockId="50.[142,758,272,815]" pageId="50" pageNumber="495">
<emphasis id="B904022DFF97FFB2FF64FEACFF200F38" box="[142,243,272,293]" italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="495">Remarks</emphasis>
: The spelling of the species name was corrected from 
<taxonomicName id="4C70A5BCFF97FFB2FEF7FE93FE500F59" authorityName=", Williams" authorityYear="1988" box="[285,387,303,324]" class="Malacostraca" family="Goneplacidae" genus="Bathyplax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="50" pageNumber="495" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="typhla">
<emphasis id="B904022DFF97FFB2FEF7FE93FE500F59" box="[285,387,303,324]" italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="495">B. typhla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to 
<taxonomicName id="4C70A5BCFF97FFB2FE46FE93FDCD0F59" authorityName="A. Milne-Edwards" authorityYear="1880" box="[428,542,303,324]" class="Malacostraca" family="Goneplacidae" genus="Bathyplax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="50" pageNumber="495" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="typhlus">
<emphasis id="B904022DFF97FFB2FE46FE93FDCD0F59" box="[428,542,303,324]" italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="495">B. typhlus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE1A3CEFF97FFB2FDA6FE93FF110F7E" author="Tavares M" pageId="50" pageNumber="495" pagination="413 - 423" refId="ref77873" refString="Tavares M. 1996. Sur la validite de Bathyplax typhlus oculiferus Miers, 1886 (Decapoda, Brachyura). Crustaceana 69 (3): 413 - 423." type="journal article" year="1996">Tavares (1996: 414)</bibRefCitation>
; the older name is unfortunately more prevalent in the literature. 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE1A3CEFF97FFB2FEBDFED0FD710F9F" author="MacDonald IR &amp; Boland GS &amp; Baker JS &amp; Brooks JM &amp; Kennicutt MC &amp; Bidigare RR" box="[343,674,364,386]" pageId="50" pageNumber="495" pagination="235 - 247" refId="ref70650" refString="MacDonald IR, Boland GS, Baker JS, Brooks JM, Kennicutt MC, Bidigare RR. 1989. Gulf of Mexico hydrocarbon seep communities II. Spatial distribution of seep organisms and hydrocarbons at Bush Hill. Marine Biology 101: 235 - 247." type="journal article" year="1989">
MacDonald 
<emphasis id="B904022DFF97FFB2FE09FED1FDC80F9C" box="[483,539,364,386]" italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="495">et al.</emphasis>
(1989: 241)
</bibRefCitation>
identified this species from still photographs and video tapes taken of ‘common slope fauna’ in the vicinity of a hydrocarbon seep (Bush Hill site) off 
<collectingRegion id="49B410DDFF97FFB2FDD2FE74FD7A0FC3" box="[568,681,456,478]" country="United States of America" name="Louisiana" pageId="50" pageNumber="495">Louisiana</collectingRegion>
in the northern 
<collectingRegion id="49B410DDFF97FFB2FF13FE5BFEF80FE0" box="[249,299,487,509]" country="Papua New Guinea" name="Gulf" pageId="50" pageNumber="495">Gulf</collectingRegion>
of 
<collectingRegion id="49B410DDFF97FFB2FEA1FE5BFE4D0FE0" box="[331,414,487,509]" country="Mexico" name="Mexico" pageId="50" pageNumber="495">Mexico</collectingRegion>
. We are not aware of any other mention of the species or genus in connection with vents or seeps. Interestingly, however, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE1A3CEFF97FFB2FD97FD98FEC30C44" author="Pequegnat LH &amp; Pequegnat WE" pageId="50" pageNumber="495" pagination="125 - 170" refId="ref74282" refString="Pequegnat LH, Pequegnat WE. 1970. Deep-sea anomurans of superfamily Galatheoidea with descriptions of three new species. In: Pequegnat WE, Chace FA Jr, eds. Contributions on the Biology of the Gulf of Mexico. Texas A &amp; M University Oceanographic Studies. Houston: Gulf Publishing Company, 125 - 170." type="book chapter" year="1970">Pequegnat (1970: 192)</bibRefCitation>
, who described the species as ‘very likely the most abundant deep-sea brachyuran in the 
<collectingRegion id="49B410DDFF97FFB2FD42FDDDFD090C6A" box="[680,730,609,631]" country="Papua New Guinea" name="Gulf" pageId="50" pageNumber="495">Gulf</collectingRegion>
of Mexico’, also noted that ‘blackened specimens are common and are probably befouled from natural oil seeps’. Goneplacids are common members of the deep-sea fauna, and it is somewhat surprising that there are so few other published reports of goneplacids in connection with vents or seeps.
</paragraph>
